On the basis of time there are mainly 2 types of polymorphism- Compile time and runtime

1. Compile time Polymorphism(static,early binding): If we are able to find at compile time that which form of the specific method will be executed is k/a compile-time polymorphism.
Because it is defined at compile time that whcih form will be executed so it is called early binding.
which method will be execute is decided by reference variable.

class A {
    public void m1(){
        System.out.println("1");
    }
    public void m1(int x){
        System.out.println(x);
    }
    public void m1(double y){
        System.out.println(y);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        A a = new A();
        a.m1();// decide at compile time
        a.m1(10);// decide at compile time
        a.m1(10.4);// decide at compile time
    }
}

examples of CTP-
method overloading:
defining multiple forms of same name method inside a class called method overloading.

